    <h1>Recent corrections</h1>
    <p class="text-ink/70 italic">
      The archive's running log of documented corrections &mdash; where what
      changed, when, and on whose authority. Family memory is treated as a
      primary source here, and a primary source can be wrong; the trail of
      correction is itself part of the record. New corrections land at the
      top.
    </p>

    <h2>2026</h2>

    <h3>June 2026 &mdash; Highland Ridge reunion portrait re-dated to c. 1971&ndash;1972</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Source of the correction: <a href="/family/roberta-burnes/">Roberta
      Burnes</a>, email June 2026.</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <a href="/archive/highland-ridge-family-group-portrait-c-1980/">labeled
      Charles Leonard Eesley extended-family reunion portrait at Highland Ridge</a>
      had been carrying the date <em>c. 1979&ndash;1985</em> based on an
      estimate of Anne Eesley's apparent age. Roberta &mdash; one of the
      labeled figures and the family's source for the print &mdash; supplied
      the controlling evidence: <em>"Katie was born in '65, and she can't be
      much more than seven years old in this picture."</em> The frame is now
      re-dated to <strong>c. 1971&ndash;1972</strong>, which places it at the
      beginning of the annual Highland Ridge reunion tradition Will and Peggy
      hosted from 1973 forward (after Charles Leonard's October 1972 death).
    </p>

    <h3>June 2026 &mdash; Aunt Ota's living-memory chain was wider than the archive had said</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Source of the correction: <a href="/family/roberta-burnes/">Roberta
      Burnes</a>, email June 2026.</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <a href="/family/mafry-smith-hyatt/">Mafry Smith Hyatt</a> page had
      claimed Mafry was <em>"the only person in this archive's record who knew
      Sciota in person."</em> Roberta corrected: <em>"Mafry and my mother both
      knew Ota, as well as all the other siblings in that generation (Len,
      Will, Don, Mary). Ota delivered my mother at home on January 16, 1924."</em>
      Aunt Ota's living-memory chain ran through the entire
      Charles-Leonard-and-Lillie-Dale sibling generation, with Helen Eesley
      Burnes (Roberta's mother) carrying the deepest set of stories &mdash;
      the X-ray burns, the c. 1929 anatomy lesson with Don, the deathbed
      narration at the Bexley house on Cassidy Avenue. The full
      <a href="/family/scioto-mafry-chenoweth/">Aunt Ota page</a> now carries
      those stories.
    </p>

    <h3>June 2026 &mdash; Verona's maiden name was Dunbar, not Sheppard</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Source of the correction: GEDCOM (Dale Eesley / FamilySearch
      sync, 1 June 2026) plus Robert Earl Wildermuth's 1989 memoir lineage
      chart.</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/family/verona-sheppard-fleming/">Verona</a>'s page had
      carried <em>"Sheppard, maiden"</em> from her daughter Sadye's 1976
      obituary. The GEDCOM and the memoir chart together correct that:
      Verona's birth surname was <strong>Dunbar</strong>, after her father
      Seth Grosvenor Dunbar of Kennebec County, Maine. <em>Sheppard</em> was
      a first married name; <em>Kelley</em> was carried as a middle name
      from her mother Martha Kelley; <em>Fleming</em> came from her marriage
      to Wesley Fleming. Two new scaffold pages followed: <a href="/family/seth-grosvenor-dunbar/">Seth
      Grosvenor Dunbar</a> and <a href="/family/martha-kelley/">Martha Kelley</a>.
    </p>

    <h3>June 2026 &mdash; "Andreus" Wildermuth corrected to Andreas Adam, birth date refined to 1745</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Source of the correction: GEDCOM (Dale Eesley / FamilySearch
      sync, 1 June 2026), cross-checked against the Rielingshausen
      <em>Kirchenbuch</em>.</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Robert Earl's 1990 Heritage spelled the deepest documented Wildermuth
      direct ancestor as <em>Andreus</em> and estimated his birth as
      <em>~1748</em>. The Rielingshausen parish register has him as
      <strong>Andreas Adam Wildermuth</strong>, born <strong>30 November
      1745</strong>, died young at 25 on 1 June 1771. The
      <a href="/family/andreus-wildermuth/">Andreus page</a> now carries the
      corrected name and date plus two additional generations recovered above
      him (Johann Adam 1720&ndash;1768, Johannes 1682). Robert Earl's
      open-question note (<em>"I have not attempted to go back any farther
      than Andreus"</em>) is preserved on the page; the correction sits next
      to it, not over it.
    </p>

    <h3>June 2026 &mdash; Ottilie Wildermuth's connection to this branch resolved</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Source of the correction: Wikipedia plus the
      Wildermuth-Gymnasium history sheet, June 2026.</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <a href="/family/ottilie-wildermuth/">Ottilie page</a> had carried
      <em>"Whether Johannes David is a direct ancestor of the Marietta
      Wildermuths or a collateral relative is not yet established in this
      archive."</em> June 2026 desk pass resolved it: Ottilie connects to the
      Marietta line <em>by marriage</em>, not descent. Her husband Wilhelm
      David Wildermuth (1807&ndash;1885) was born in <em>Pleidelsheim</em>,
      one of the three Marbach-district villages the 1990 Heritage names as
      Wildermuth heartland. The two American branches (the Tübingen line
      Ottilie married into, the Marietta line Johann Michael founded in 1847)
      are extended cousins through the Rielingshausen clan documented from
      1521. The Tübingen Wildermuth-Gymnasium and the Marbach
      Wildermuthstraße are named for <em>that</em> branch; the Marietta line
      is the <em>other</em> American twig of the same root.
    </p>

    <h3>June 2026 &mdash; Jean Goldie Eesley's dates corrected and the car-crash story added</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Sources of the correction: GEDCOM (1 June 2026) settled the
      dates; Roberta Burnes's June 2026 email supplied the cause-of-death
      story from her mother's memory.</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Mary Bean's 1985 register had carried <em>"b. Oct. 28, 1912, Grove
      City Ohio. d. died 1924, Columbus Ohio,"</em> making
      <a href="/family/jean-goldie-eesley/">Jean</a> twelve at death. The
      GEDCOM has 28 October 1921 to 13 October 1925 (age 4) &mdash; nine
      years off from the 1985 register. Charlie's 1965 12th-grade
      autobiography said <em>"my Aunt Jean died from a childhood accident
      when she was five years old."</em> Roberta's June 2026 email puts a
      clinical picture on the accident: Jean was thrown from the family
      vehicle in a crash, hit pavement, suffered a concussion, appeared
      stable for hours, then died overnight from what reads as a delayed
      brain bleed. Aunt Ota was the family physician who treated her.
    </p>

    <h3>June 2026 &mdash; Mill sign was not from a 2026 visit; the family hasn't been there yet</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Source of the correction: Chuck Eesley, June 2026.</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      The <a href="/places/plainwell-eesley-mill/">Plainwell Eesley mill page</a>
      had attributed an Eesley Mill sign photograph to a visit. Chuck
      corrected: the sign photo was <em>not</em> from a visit; he is hoping
      to visit Plainwell in November 2026. The place page was rewritten as a
      forecast (<code>status: unreached</code>) rather than a visit account.
    </p>

    <h3>June 2026 &mdash; Vietnam letters re-dated to 1969&ndash;1971</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Source of the correction: Chuck Eesley, June 2026.</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Several pages and the <a href="/docs/letters-from-vietnam/">collection
      doc</a> had carried <em>1970&ndash;71</em> for Charlie's tour. Charlie
      shipped to Vietnam in October 1969 (NCO school summer 1969, deployment
      that fall), and rotated out in 1971. The dates were updated across the
      letter docs and on
      <a href="/family/charles-eesley/">Charlie's page</a>.
    </p>

    <h3>June 2026 &mdash; Lijie's Chinese name confirmed as 周丽婕</h3>
