    </p>

    <h2>How the correction trail works</h2>
    <p>
      Three principles run through this log:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Corrections are documented in place first.</strong> When a
        date or fact changes, the prior reading and the correction trail stay
        on the page where the original claim appeared. This log is the
        aggregation, not the substitute.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The source of every correction is named.</strong> Whether the
        correction came from a family-member email, a GEDCOM sync, a German
        Wikipedia entry, or Chuck's own memory, the source is on the page
        and on this log.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Earlier readings are preserved, not erased.</strong> Mary
        Bean's 1985 register entry for Jean Goldie is still recorded on
        Jean's page next to the corrected GEDCOM dates; Robert Earl's
        <em>"Andreus"</em> spelling is still on the Andreas Adam page next
        to the parish-register name. The archive treats earlier sources as
        primary sources too &mdash; even when they turn out to have been
        wrong about a date.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      If you have a correction to submit, the easiest route is an email
      to Chuck. New corrections that arrive after this log was last
      updated will appear at the top with the same fields: date the
      correction was made, what changed, source.
    </p>

